Airbnb New User Bookings Prediction

Carreen de Cardenas

11/28/2017

About Airbnb and the Project Goals

Airbnb is an online marketplace that creates an outlet for people to list, discover, and book unique living accommodations around the world. The company was founded in 2008 and is based in San Francisco, but Airbnb can now be found in more than 65,000 cities, 191 countries and over 200,000,000 guest have used the service.

The main question we are asking with this dataset and project is Where will a new guest book their first travel experience?

Accurately predicting where a new user will book for their first travel experience would allow Airbnb to personalize content, decrease the average time to first book, and better forecast demand.

US - United States FR - France CA - Canada GB - Great Britain ES - Spain IT - Italy PT - Portugal NL - Netheralands DE - Germany AU - Austrailia NDF - no destination found or no booking other - Booking but not in one of the other 180 countries

Gradient Boosted Trees Model

Some of the categories of data given didnt seem to relate to the destination where users booked, so those variables were not included in the model. The following categories either hurt or did not benefit the predictiveness of the model for example, and thus left out of the model:

timestamp_first_active: Adding this as a factor lowered the accuracy of the prediction. There were very small differences in the timestamps entered.

date_first_booking: Because the goal is to predict what the first booking will be, using this may help predict on this set but would not be useful when predicting first time users.

language: All users are from the US so almost all of the users had english as a preferred language so that would not effect the prediction.

form <- country_destination ~ date_account_created + gender + age + signup_method + signup_flow + affiliate_channel + affiliate_provider + signup_app + first_device_type + first_browser

X_train <- model.matrix(form, data = users[users$train_id == "train",])
y_train <- model.response(model.frame(form, data = users[users$train_id == "train",]))

X_test <- model.matrix(form, data = users[users$train_id == "test",])
y_test <- model.response(model.frame(form, data = users[users$train_id == "test",]))

This dataset did not have all the data for each user which caused some issues when creating the X_train, y_train, X_test, and y_test. I kept getting errors about the logical subcript being too long. R was removing the missing rows when creating the dataset, which threw everyting off. Writing the code as above using the model.frame, model.matrix and model.response mitigated this issue.

The next step was to get turn the country destinations into number values so we could run the model:

cats <- unique(y_train)
y_train <- match(y_train, cats) - 1
y_test <- match(y_test, cats) - 1

multi:softmax was used as the objective so the above code had to use the -1 to the values from 0-11, because the class is represented by a number and should be from 0 to num_class -1 for the function to be used. We can then use xgboost to do multiclass classification using the softmax objective.

model <- xgboost(data = X_train, label = y_train,
                 max_depth = 3, eta = 0.001, nthread = 20,
                 nrounds = 20, objective = "multi:softmax",
                 verbose = 1, num_class = length(cats))

Results

Using the model above we can see what the prediction rate is for this model:

y_test_pred <- predict(model, newdata = X_test)
mean(y_test == y_test_pred)
## [1] 0.5304947
table(y_test, y_test_pred)

A prediction rate of 0.5349191 is relatively high considering there are 12 categories so random guessing would only 1/12 which is only 0.08333, so by using this xgboost model Airbnb would be able to drastically improve their prediction of where first time users will book their first accomodation. Being able to tailor their advertisement, Airbnb will be able to create a more efficent service and would create a better experience for the users.
